ðŸ”¹ What is Selection Sort? (Say this)

Selection Sort repeatedly finds the minimum element from the unsorted part and places it at the correct position.

ðŸ§  KEY IDEA (VERY IMPORTANT)

Bubble Sort â†’ swap again & again

Selection Sort â†’ only ONE swap per pass






public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Step 1: Declare and initialize array
        int[] arr = {64, 25, 12, 22, 11};

        // Step 2: Outer loop
        // This loop decides the position where the smallest element will be placed
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) {

            // Step 3: Assume current index has the minimum element
            int minIndex = i;

            // Step 4: Inner loop
            // This loop finds the minimum element from the unsorted part
            for (int j = i + 1; j < arr.length; j++) {

                // Step 5: Compare current element with assumed minimum
                if (arr[j] < arr[minIndex]) {
                    // Step 6: Update minIndex if smaller element found
                    minIndex = j;
                }
            }

            // Step 7: Swap after inner loop
            // Now we are sure which element is the smallest
            int temp = arr[minIndex];
            arr[minIndex] = arr[i];
            arr[i] = temp;
        }

        // Step 8: Print sorted array
        for (int x : arr) {
            System.out.print(x + " ");
        }
    }
}

Q1ï¸âƒ£ Time Complexity?

Best: O(nÂ²)
Average: O(nÂ²)
Worst: O(nÂ²)


| Bubble Sort         | Selection Sort       |
| ------------------- | -------------------- |
| Many swaps          | Only 1 swap per pass |
| Compare neighbors   | Compare with minimum |
| Largest moves right | Smallest moves left  |

